    origin: "Mediterranean region; native to dry coastal cliffs, valleys, and scrublands of Southern Europe and North Africa where it evolved to withstand intense sunlight, poor soils, salty winds, and prolonged drought conditions. It has since naturalized widely across temperate and subtropical regions due to its hardiness and cultural spread through trade and culinary influence.",
    plantType: "A woody perennial herb belonging to the Lamiaceae (mint) family. It forms a long-lived evergreen shrub that retains foliage year-round, capable of surviving 15–20 years or more under suitable conditions. Its structure becomes more gnarled and woody with age, contributing to its distinctive ornamental appearance.",
    appearance: "Rosmarinus features slender, needle-like leaves arranged oppositely along woody stems. The leaves are dark green on top with a silvery, resin-rich underside that helps reduce water loss. Small tubular flowers—typically blue or lavender, sometimes white or pale pink—appear along the upper nodes and are rich in nectar. The plant has a fresh pine-like fragrance due to essential oils stored in leaf glands. Mature plants develop a dense shrub form with rugged, brown bark and upright to arching growth depending on variety.",
    propagationMethods: "Propagation is most successful through semi-hardwood stem cuttings taken in late spring to early summer, which root quickly with warmth and humidity. Seed propagation is possible but slow, often requiring stratification and variable germination rates. Air layering and ground layering can also be used for older woody stems. Professional growers prefer cuttings for consistency in growth habit and essential oil profile.",
    commonPestsAndDiseases: "Although generally resilient, rosemary may attract aphids, spider mites, whiteflies, and occasionally scale insects, particularly in sheltered or indoor environments. Fungal diseases such as powdery mildew and botrytis can occur in high humidity or overcrowding. Root rot and damping-off are common when soil drainage is poor or watering is excessive. Good airflow, full sun, and minimal moisture around the foliage help prevent most issues.",
    PlantUses: "Rosmarinus is prized as a culinary seasoning for roasted meats, bread, oils, vegetables, and marinades due to its strong aromatic compounds. Medicinally, it has been used traditionally to ease digestive discomfort, stimulate circulation, improve concentration, and support hair health. Its essential oils—rich in cineole, camphor, and borneol—are widely used in soaps, perfumery, bath products, aromatherapy blends, and natural insect repellents. Culturally, rosemary has been associated with memory, remembrance, protection, and ritual use since ancient Greek and Roman times.",
    Precautions: "Rosmarinus essential oil can cause irritation if applied undiluted to sensitive skin. Internal use in large doses is not recommended for pregnant individuals, those with epilepsy, blood pressure complications, or individuals on certain medications, unless supervised by a qualified practitioner. Allergic contact dermatitis may occur in sensitive individuals. While safe as a culinary herb, concentrated extracts and oils should be used responsibly.",
    EcologicalImportance: "A valuable plant for dry ecosystems, rosemary provides abundant nectar to support bees, butterflies, hoverflies, and other pollinators throughout its long blooming period. Its deep and fibrous root system helps stabilize slopes and prevent erosion in Mediterranean landscapes. The dense shrub structure offers habitat and shelter for beneficial garden insects. Its ability to thrive in poor soils makes it a sustainable landscaping choice for xeriscapes (low-water gardens).",
    SeasonalCalendar: "Best planted in spring or fall when mild temperatures encourage rapid root development. Flowering commonly occurs from late spring to midsummer, although repeat blooming may occur in mild or coastal climates. Pruning is recommended after flowering to promote compact growth and discourage woody legginess. Fertilization needs are minimal and usually applied in early spring if growth appears weak.",
    GrowthStatics: "Mature shrubs can reach 1–2 meters in height and spread 1–1.5 meters wide, though dwarf and upright cultivars vary in form. Growth rate is moderate but increases significantly under full sun and well-drained soils. When grown in poor or rocky soils, rosemary maintains a tighter habit with stronger aromatic concentration in the oils.",
    ScientificRearch: "Research identifies rosemary as a rich source of biologically active compounds including rosmarinic acid, carnosol, carnosic acid, and multiple flavonoids. These demonstrate antioxidant, antimicrobial, anti-inflammatory, and cognitive-enhancing effects in laboratory studies. Ongoing research explores applications in natural food preservation, anti-aging formulations, memory enhancement, cancer-inhibitory activity, and neuroprotective support against Alzheimer's-related processes.",
    SoilPHPreference: "Performs best in slightly acidic to neutral soils between pH 6.0 and 7.5. Prefers sandy, gravelly, or decomposed rocky substrates with excellent drainage. Heavy clay soils should be amended with grit or planted on raised mounds to prevent root rot. Nutrient-poor soil often increases aroma intensity due to higher production of essential oils.",
    WateringNeeds: "Young plants require moderate and consistent moisture until established. Once mature, rosemary becomes highly drought-tolerant and thrives with minimal irrigation. Excess watering can stress the plant, reduce aroma strength, and increase fungal issues. Deep but infrequent watering promotes strong root systems. Indoor container plants should be watered only when the top soil is fully dry.",
    RepottingInformation: "Container-grown rosemary typically needs repotting every 2–3 years in early spring. Transplanting into a slightly larger pot with sharp-draining soil (such as sand- or grit-amended mix) restores vitality. Mature plants benefit from light root pruning and removal of compacted soil. Repotting also provides an opportunity to reshape the plant and encourage fresh young growth.",
    read: "Rosmarinus officinalis, commonly known as rosemary, has been cherished for millennia as both a culinary herb and a medicinal plant. Originating in the Mediterranean basin, rosemary's hardy nature and aromatic qualities made it a staple in ancient Greek, Roman, and Egyptian cultures. It was revered for its ability to enhance memory, purify the air, and provide protection against evil spirits. Culinary traditions embraced rosemary for its robust flavor, pairing it with roasted meats, vegetables, and breads. Medicinally, rosemary was used to stimulate digestion, improve circulation, and support cognitive function. The essential oils extracted from rosemary leaves have found widespread use in aromatherapy, cosmetics, and natural remedies. Modern scientific research has validated many of rosemary's traditional uses, identifying potent antioxidant and anti-inflammatory compounds that contribute to its health benefits. Today, rosemary continues to be a beloved herb that bridges ancient wisdom with contemporary culinary and wellness practices.",
    "iframe": "<iframe title=\"Rosemary Plant - Sketchfab\" class=\"c-viewer__iframe\" src=\"https://sketchfab.com/models/d5c0f249ff8a4d13840abf681bb92d29/embed?autostart=1&amp;internal=1&amp;tracking=0&amp;ui_ar=0&amp;ui_infos=0&amp;ui_snapshots=1&amp;ui_stop=0&amp;ui_theatre=1&amp;ui_watermark=0\" id=\"api-frame\" allow=\"autoplay; fullscreen; xr-spatial-tracking\" xr-spatial-tracking=\"true\" execution-while-out-of-viewport=\"true\" execution-while-not-rendered=\"true\" web-share=\"true\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe>"
