  origin: "Garlic is one of the oldest cultivated plants, believed to have originated in Central Asia, particularly regions of modern-day Iran and Turkmenistan. From there, it spread through ancient trade routes to the Middle East, Mediterranean, Egypt, China, and eventually the rest of the world. It has been a staple in food, medicine, and cultural rituals for more than 5,000 years and is now cultivated globally in temperate and subtropical regions.",
  plantType: "Garlic is a hardy, herbaceous perennial grown annually for its bulbs. It belongs to the Amaryllidaceae family, along with onions and leeks. Although treated as an annual crop, it technically regrows each season through its underground cloves.",
  appearance: "Garlic plants produce narrow, flat, linear leaves arising from a central pseudostem. The underground bulb consists of multiple cloves encased in papery skin ranging from white and cream to purple depending on variety. Hardneck types produce a flowering stalk called a scape with small aerial bulbils, while softneck types lack a rigid central stem and are commonly used for braiding.",
  propagationMethods: "Garlic is most commonly propagated by planting individual cloves, each capable of forming a new bulb genetically identical to the parent. Planting usually occurs in fall or early winter to allow root establishment before spring growth. Hardneck garlic also produces bulbils that can be planted but may require one to two years to mature into full bulbs.",
  commonPestsAndDiseases: "Garlic may face fungal diseases like white rot, downy mildew, rust, and fusarium basal rot, especially in wet soils or when crop rotation is not practiced. Thrips, onion maggots, nematodes, and mites can also affect bulb quality. Planting in well-drained soils, rotating crops, and avoiding overhead watering help reduce disease pressure.",
  PlantUses: "Garlic is one of the most widely consumed culinary herbs, valued for its strong, pungent flavor in nearly every global cuisine. Medicinally, it has long been used to support heart health, digestion, immune strength, detoxification, and respiratory well-being. Its active compound allicin is known for potent antimicrobial, antiviral, antifungal, and cholesterol-lowering effects. Garlic is also used in herbal tonics, extracts, oils, poultices, and dietary supplements.",
  Precautions: "Although safe as a food ingredient, excessive consumption on an empty stomach may cause digestive irritation. Garlic may increase bleeding risk when combined with anticoagulant or antiplatelet medications. Fresh juice or strong raw preparations may irritate sensitive skin if applied topically.",
  EcologicalImportance: "Garlic contributes to sustainable agriculture through natural pest deterrence. Its sulfur-rich compounds repel many insects and soil pathogens, making it useful in companion planting. Certain wild pollinators visit garlic flowers, while the plant supports soil health by reducing harmful microbial populations.",
  SeasonalCalendar: "Typically planted in autumn to allow cloves to establish roots before winter dormancy. Active leaf growth resumes in early spring, with bulbs swelling in late spring to early summer. Harvest occurs when around one-third of the leaves have dried. Bulbs are cured for several weeks to improve storage and flavor.",
  GrowthStatics: "Individual plants generally reach 30–90 cm in height. Bulbs range from 4–8 cm in diameter depending on variety and growing conditions. Yield and size improve in cool climates followed by warm springs and early summers.",
  ScientificRearch: "Extensive modern research highlights garlic’s allicin and related organosulfur compounds as key bioactive constituents. Studies support significant antioxidant, antibacterial, antiviral, antifungal, anti-inflammatory, and cardioprotective effects. Research demonstrates benefits in reducing high cholesterol, moderating blood pressure, supporting immune response, and even showing potential anti-cancer activity in laboratory investigations.",
  SoilPHPreference: "Best grown in loose, fertile, well-drained soil with a pH between 6.0 and 7.5. Heavy clay soil can restrict bulb expansion and increase disease susceptibility; raised beds and compost improve performance.",
